He just got off of work at the base and was still in his uniform and  I remember feeling proud and special walking out of the theater holding his hand. (he served in the Navy from 1963-1970 as mechanic then a pilot on the USS Wasp finding astronauts in the ocean. He then served again from 1981-1982,in the Navy reserves. Comment: I spent my childhood watching the first film with my dad, it was his favorite and he always talked excitedly about one day being able to watch a sequel together at the cinema. For years he fought an illness and couldn't resist the last blow, I couldn't help but remember him when I found out that there would be a sequel to Top Gun, on the day of the premiere I spent the entire film emotional and at the end I couldn't contain my tears when I looked at the empty chair next to me and to think that my father could be there clapping and smiling. Comment:
¬†@yogiritakatou8471¬† Lol maverick had no real plot... The entire movie made no sense and never comes together! NOTHING seperated the top gun pilots from one another, except bob who had one job... Mav picks the only mission possible... oh wait I can literally think of 5 other possibilites that DO NOT endanger the lives of 4 other pilots... The love interest made no sense. The drama with Rooster made no sense. They never explain  what makes a 5th gen fighter better. Mav blows up a multi million dollar aircraft at mach 10 and just parachutes away? You're dead if your plane explodes at any mach... If you're going 10 times the speed of sound and your aircraft explodes, you're dead. You cannot eject at that speed, but somehow saves the project after destroying the only craft, and then transfers to top gun, with the officer that managed the project... I didn't know you can just take people with you when you're ordered to another base... 
Ice man suddenly dying, the love interest, both made no sense at all. Ice mans overdramatic funeral as if he died saving a child or something. Its silly. 
Mav could do it all, but decides to take the pilots who show no demonstrable skill at all on what is seemingly a suicide mission to take out a base that only manufactures or something... and there is no other door or anyting, but a fucking vent at the top of a percectly shaped mountain for SAM defense and whatever. 
I learned nothing about aeronautics, flying, or even the navy for that matter. Connely was in the movie only to hold onto Tom as they ride without a helmet on, as if that adds to the excitement of riding, and you cant ride without a helmet on in this state, even on a military base... They get upset with Mav for going below the harddeck, but dont seem to care when he carelessly and DANGEROUSLY flies between two aircraft at TOP speed... Yeah, bull shit. They dont even like flyovers... Hence the first film. 
So this was just a stringy 40 year old sequel that actually went nowhere... 
The ending was the worst part... Hangman saves them? And then they have this mimic bullshit bro mmoment with rooster and hangman? What  drama did they have? Oh yeah that two minutes of bravado between who is better as they walk around the base... But nonetheless the douchebag in the movie saves them by shooting down a 5th gen aircraft who apparantly doesn't have radar, doesn't know there is a missile lock on him or anything... So hangman destroys a tough enemy and never showed any skill in doing so but they make a big deal about how its so hard to fight this aircraft.. Does that make sense? 
They were worried about the SAM rockets, which travel subsonic, but seemed to dodge them without radar, but using their eyes and tonal beeps to help them... In reality, most likely all died. When rooster says he is out of flares, the rocket would have reached him as he is still flying straight... Miraculously and totally stupid, mav just once again parachutes away... 
The fact it made money, well tom wouldn't release it in any other format, and theaters make a killing on premiers and movie-goers, so thats irrelavant. The movie was only exciting when mav is shot down, and then the finale is ruined by the ridiculous bromance with hangman (who showed no real skill) and Rooster (who didn't show much skill either...)

Comment:
¬†Jay Bee¬†  It's true I haven't seen the film; guess I should give it a chance first! I loved the first movie too! Sequels are rarely as good and often Hollywood just milks things to death.. Cruise has done a good job of keeping himself fit and interesting, so good on him and great he has so many fans still. Honestly - since you speak of honesty - I'm a bit jealous. I'm not being a downer "for its own sake": why would I? I am being a Debbie Downer, though. I've always been a bit cynical and critical: it's what I think: oh well! It actually comes from a desire to do my Own stuff. Have done some small things.. Recently, had an unexpected medical problem that took my dreams right out, for the most part. That's what happens if one hesitates too long.. 
   I Still just don't like CGI and fake stuff as much as older stuff. Like with animation (cartoons): I'll always admire the craft of the old-school Disney stuff; computerized stuff has a coldness to it, and drawings can feel more realistic even though they're Not as precise: the imagination fills in the rest. 
   It's true I've never been quick to embraces change. It's probably a flaw: not keeping up or something. But maybe it's just me. People differ. We all have a right to our opinions. 
   I don't see why you leap to "I dont understand people, movies", etc just because I disagree with you and Lots of people. I did see at least one negative review from a professional. Greatly in the minority but it still existed. People on YouTube are so vicious sometimes, it's a waste of time; I forgot what a bad habit it is.

Comment:
I am Japanese.
Sorry for my poor English.
I can't resist commenting here too.

Top Gun Maverick is a part of my life.
I've seen it 53 times at the cinema.
 (2024/05/17)


Top Gun is also very popular in Japan.
In Japan, a phenomenon known as "Chasing Top Gun" emerged and was loved for a long time.

Grand Cinema Sunshine Ikebukuro in Tokyo has the largest IMAX in Japan.
When we show a film there, the seats fill up quickly, even on weekdays.

I have seen Maverick 10 times in IMAX at Grand Cinema Sunshine Ikebukuro. Among them, March 3, 2023 and January 11, 2024 were particularly moving and unforgettable memories.

After the end credits rolled, applause erupted in the theater.

In Japan, applause in movie theaters is an extremely rare phenomenon.

That's how much Top Gun Maverick excited and moved so many people, and received such great support.

Of course, I was one of those who was enthusiastic, moved, and applauded.

Sorry for repeating myself.
TOP GUN MAVERICK is a part of life.

Don't think, just do!

¬†@Anthony-pk8lb¬† if you‚Äôre moving at a constant speed, it won‚Äôt matter how fast you‚Äôre going, you won‚Äôt feel a thing. The earth moves at about Mach 87 as it goes around the sun, but we don‚Äôt feel it. 

What the body cannot stand is the force caused by high acceleration. One G is the equivalent of the force due to earth‚Äôs gravity. When a plane makes a sharp turn, you can feel the force equivalent to multiple times the acceleration of gravity. A high intensity roller coaster can exert about 3-4G‚Äôs. Comment:
The flight scenes look well done? 
Which ones:
-The ridiculously sped up Mach Loop-esque sequence at 0:23?
-The very obvious and dangerous CGI that would get any pilot permanently grounded at 1:03?
-The weird 1950s style helmets they're wearing onwards from 1:16?
-The cat-launched unarmed Hornet at 1:24 that's suddenly carrying inert, training LGBs at 1:25 (and who go into combat with them at 1:39)?
-The unnecessarily tight formation just to get four planes into a single frame at 1:50?
-The ancient, super CGI SA-3 Goa(!) SAM ripple firing(!!) 1960s era missiles at 1:59?
-or the Hornet-Es that switch to Hornet-Fs and back again in the different trailers?

We must have different understandings on what 'well done' is all about-- have a look at Sky Fighters (2005) for well made flight sequences without leaning on *any* meh CGI. Do yourselves a favour, go into this expecting Stealth. If you go in expecting Top Gun '86, you'll be disappointed. If you go in expecting Stealth, you'll enjoy yourselves much more.

Comment: Just watched Top Gun: Maverick yesterday in the theaters!  WOW AMAZING!  Tom Cruise should win an award for his flying  - It was off the charts! The skill required is beyond fathomable. There is no doubt this man has mastered the physicality of acting. It would be hardly proper to discuss this movie without mentioning the spectacular cinematography. It's apparent that great strides went into capturing the visual essence beyond the well-written dramatic storyline. Tom Cruises' now aged character Maverick is relatable. For example, the characterization of being older and the feeling of insignificance as time has passed by, while trying to find ones place in life. Even more importantly defending ones place in life - Maverick has chosen not to become a high-ranking official after thirty-some years, but pursue what makes him happy and fulfilled. The challenge that we all face at one point is trying to earn trust and respect. Dealing with and reconciling the pains of the past. Integrity plays a big part in this role, doing what is right which may be harder than not. One might think from the trailer this movie is about the military and aviation but it's much deeper. As a side note, I always enjoy John Hamm in leadership roles from Don Draper in Mad Men, to Admiral Beau Simpson, Mavericks antagonist.  Definetly a cinema movie. If you saw this in the theater, you're one of the lucky ones!

Comment: So here is my movie review. Do not read any further if you don't like realness. I feel like this movie should have been made 15 years ago. Tom Cruise is in good shape for his age but it feels like he is to old to be still in the air force flying jets. It felt like he's the one that should have been giving the orders not taking them. Also apparently he was single with no kids in the movie.  That seems highly unlikely being that he was kind of a playboy in the movie unless he was keeping a secret. Another thing is it was nice seeing Val Kilmer but having him die in the movie seems kind of cringey and disrespectful being that he had cancer in real life. It would have been better if Maverick got  killed which almost happened  a couple times toward the end. It was kind of cheesy when he was saved by Hangman.  The soundtrack sucked. Compared to the original movie which produced some classic 80s hits. Even the acting was mediocre.  Tom Cruise seemed like he wasn't putting alot of effort into his role. Jon Hamm was basically miscast in his role. He just didn't suit that role. He's not intimidating.  The most believable and best job was done by Bashir Salahuddin. I don't know to me the cast didn't have any chemistry.  So that is my movie review.  Take it or leave it.

Comment:
Sorry but this movie was a total dud... The plot made no sense, the Top Gun graduates were selected for their qualifications but we never actually see them qualify for anything... Only BOB actually seemed to be particular to the script and story... Everyone else was just this weird hot shot that had no reason to be so arrogant... When Mav picks his team, there is literally NOTHING that established any of them as good or even worthy of the mission... 
THE MISSION: Made no sense whatsoever... Mav walks in, decides in two minutes how this mission will go and the only way it will go... Mentiioning some odd number generation fighter jets that the enemy has and we for whatever reason can only use outdated aircraft... WHY?! YOu can still use a Raptor and other jets to be on standby to take out the enemy fighters as they pursue the attacking force... 
Furthermore, I can think of at least three other ways to take out this TOTALLY unimportant base that only PRODUCES dangerous stuff... THERE ARE LITERALLY A MILLION WAYS TO HANDLE THAT
But Mav does it all... He constantly in every scene! How about special forces HALO in, laser guide the rocket, and/or take out the sam turrets one by one... The base seemingly had NO GUARDS anywhere to see 4 military planes flying in... So why just have special forces do it all? They could have used strike missiles (like they did to take out the runway) to take out the SAM rockets as their planes approached and then that way their is less SAM's and blah blah. Surface to air missiles are incredibly dangerous. Some can go subsonic... Yet they just dodge a whole bunch like whatever. You cant even see them, you use your radar. Basically, they're dead. 
Again, Mav can do it all and shows that he can do it by himself, but decides to take 3 other planes and risk the lives of 4 other pilots to do essentially a suicide mission, Knowing that the pilots are not ready and have showed no real prowess in flying leading up to the mission itself... 
The training they do for the mission: MAV SMOKES THEM ALL! NOBODY EVER SEEMS TO PROGRESS! We learn nothing about aeronautics (unlike the first film), nothing about why 5th gen fighters are better, and NOTHING about what it is to be in the NAVY. 
He tries to save a military project worth seemingly millions by taking it to match 10, but then deliberately pushes it beyond its limit and miraculously surviving as it explodes... Look, when you go 10 times the speed of sound and your plane explodes, you're fucking dead... THere is no time to hit the ejector and if you did, you're still dead... So destroying the only plane didn't and could not have saved or bought that team time, but nonetheless Mav takes the other officer with him to Top Gun? I didn't know you can just take people with you when you get transferred... Who is running that project now? lol dumb
Jennifer Connely: Why is she even in this movie? I could care less that she went sailing with her daughter at the end because they never establish any real connection... Shewas with him for both Iraq missions... Thats literally 20+ years apart from gulf war to Iraq war... Soooo thats a long time... But she says to him, lets not do this again, but then she does it again... She was only there to hold on to Tom as he rides a motorcycle... I didn't know you could ride a Motorcycle in California, or any military base without a helmet on... The beginning of the film he has an 80's streetbike but then later he has the latest Ninja which is custom made to the rider... Just odd to have that all of a sudden. 
The 'drama' with Rooster was silly and useless. Everyone knows Mav was not at fault. Gooses own wife said it wasn't his fault. There was literally no way to save the plane and no way to know that anyone would die from hitting the cockpit window... Yet, rooster is bitter, dresses just like his dad, and then sings a song that he saw his dad sing when he was 4 years old... 
I love how every grad student from Top GUn walks into a bar, Nobody is tired, nobody has anything else to say but smart ass comment after smart ass comment.. Every line was just smart ass comment to a reply from a smart ass comment... For whatever reason Hangman ends up saving the day, and then they bullshit the rooster hangman drama like iceman and mav... its stupid. Hangman literally showed no more skill than anyone else but gets another kill from a 5th gen fighter who had NO IDEA he was being locked onto? 
WHy did iceman die? I know Val is sick but does iceman have the same issues? he just drops dead and then mav does this incredibly emotional goodbye as if Iceman died in combat saving the world... No reason to do that. I was actually angererd by this pathetic excuse for drama. The sex scene was weird... their laying there and they dont even look like they had sex... And the daughter catching him like he is 22 sneaking out and telling him not to hurt her mom again... like little kid, YOUR MOM IS DOING IT! She's the enabler. And Mav looking at her like oh snap, you're right  was just CHEESY as hell.

In the end, if you made it this far, the movie was boring and silly. Even the critics... One critic said the movie was okay, but it was Toms smile... WTF does that have to do with anything? It seems the only fascination with this movie is in fact that smile because it is all over this movie. That or seeing Tom cruise play the same character from 40 years ago... If you're the person who is blown away to see Tom or Harrison play Mav or Han, you're just easy to please.   It feels like Covid hampered production and they minimalized the story to make the movie happen with what was probably a struggle.
